The KEY_VALUES_MISMATCH error indicates that the private key in server.key does not match the public key in server1.pem. Here are steps to resolve this:

1. Verify Key and Certificate Match
You can check if the private key and certificate match by comparing their modulus values. Run these commands in your terminal:

openssl rsa -noout -modulus -in C:\Users\shank\Downloads\server.key | openssl md5
openssl x509 -noout -modulus -in C:\Users\shank\Downloads\server1.pem | openssl md5

The output of both commands should be identical. If they are not, the key and certificate do not match.

1. Generate Matching Key and Certificate
If the key and certificate do not match, you will need to generate a new pair. Here’s how you can do it:

Download openssl [Win32/Win64 OpenSSL Installer for Windows - Shining Light Productions (slproweb.com)](https://slproweb.com/products/Win32OpenSSL.html)

Generate a New Private Key:
openssl genrsa -out server.key 2048

Generate a Certificate Signing Request (CSR):
openssl req -new -key server.key -out server.csr

Generate a Self-Signed Certificate:
openssl x509 -req -days 365 -in server.csr -signkey server.key -out server.pem

1. Update Your Code
Ensure your code points to the correct files:

python

import socketserver
import http.server
import ssl

# Create an SSL context

context = ssl.SSLContext(ssl.PROTOCOL_TLS_SERVER)
context.load_cert_chain(certfile=r"C:\Users\shank\Downloads\server.pem", keyfile=r"C:\Users\shank\Downloads\server.key")

httpd = socketserver.TCPServer(('0.0.0.0', 10000), http.server.SimpleHTTPRequestHandler)
httpd.socket = context.wrap_socket(httpd.socket, server_side=True)

httpd.serve_forever()
